   "source": [
    "# Creating Spherical Galaxy Clusters\n",
    "![author_button](https://img.shields.io/badge/Written_By:-Eliza_Diggins-blue)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "This example will walk you through generating a spherically symmetric galaxy cluster using Pisces. Galaxy clusters are (in idealized models) spherically symmetric systems with a gasseous intra-cluster plasma (the ICM) which is supported against collapse by thermal pressure, a host dark matter halo, and a stellar component. In many cases, the stellar component may be left out as it has a minimal impact on the ICM in simulations. In this case, we're going to do the following:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. We'll create a generic spherical geometry object from ``pisces.geometry.coordinate_systems``.\n",
    "2. We'll initialize our galaxy cluster using two [NFW Profiles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Navarro%E2%80%93Frenk%E2%80%93White_profile), one for the gas density\n",
    "   and one for the total density.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can then pass this information to the model and it will compute the necessary fields to complete the model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "259906af-96c9-474f-8599-1b3d08a23c92",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Import Pisces and other necessary structures.\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from pisces.geometry.coordinate_systems import SphericalCoordinateSystem\n",
    "from pisces.models.galaxy_clusters import ClusterModel"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "15c07aa4-fa21-4175-863a-09dcc171a6bb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The first thing to do is initialize the coordinate system object. In general, a coordinate system might require arguments, but the spherical coordinate system is a particularly simple case."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "50e3adad-3290-44ff-9e82-5303f0c239b9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Pisces : [INFO     ] 2025-01-07 14:10:19,363 Preparing Lame Coefficients for SphericalCoordinateSystem instance. This may take a few seconds...\n",
      "Pisces : [INFO     ] 2025-01-07 14:10:19,444 Preparing derived attributes for SphericalCoordinateSystem instance. This may take a few seconds...\n",
      "Pisces : [INFO     ] 2025-01-07 14:10:19,447 Lambdifying attributes...\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "coordinate_system = SphericalCoordinateSystem()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dfe5a180-515c-4475-bac2-da16ab1346da",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now that we have a coordinate system, the next task is to build the profiles for our galaxy clusters. We want two NFW profiles of the correct general properties to be valid for a galaxy cluster. The NFW profiles in Pisces require a $\\rho_0$ and $r_s$ parameter to be specified. Generally, $r_s$ is on the order of 100's of kpc in galaxy clusters. For such a system, the virial radius is $\\sim 4 r_s$ and so the virial mass is similar to\n",
    "\n",
    "$$M_{\\rm vir} \\approx 1.4 \\left[\\frac{4}{3}\\rho_0\\pi r_s^3\\right] \\implies \\rho_0 \\approx \\frac{3M_{\\rm vir}}{4 \\pi r_s^3}.$$\n",
    "\n",
    "For a virial mass around $10^{15}\\,{\\rm M}_{\\odot},$ we need a $\\rho_0 \\sim 1 \\times 10^7 {\\rm \\frac{M_\\odot}{kpc^3}}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll have the gas profile carry a slightly steeper scale radius and about 1/10 of the density."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "a261fe0b-a6d7-403a-9528-51f0e0f08720",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Import the density profile class from the density\n",
    "# module of the profiles library.\n",
    "from pisces.profiles.density import NFWDensityProfile\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the halo and gas profiles.\n",
    "halo_profile = NFWDensityProfile(rho_0=1e7, r_s=200)\n",
    "gas_profile = NFWDensityProfile(rho_0=1e6, r_s=150)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "3e55bce8-b922-47c4-9e4b-4fa4476926f3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Text(0, 0.5, 'Density, $\\\\left[{\\\\rm M_\\\\odot / kpc^3}\\\\right]$')"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 7,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Plot the two profiles over a characteristic range of radii.\n",
    "x = np.geomspace(1e-1, 1e4, 1000)\n",
    "halo_density, gas_density = halo_profile(x), gas_profile(x)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes.loglog(x, halo_density, color=\"darkblue\", label=r\"$\\rho_{\\rm DM}(r)$\")\n",
    "axes.loglog(x, gas_density, color=\"darkgreen\", label=r\"$\\rho_{\\rm g}(r)$\")\n",
    "axes.set_xlabel(\"Radii, [kpc]\")\n",
    "axes.set_ylabel(r\"Density, $\\left[{\\rm M_\\odot / kpc^3}\\right]$\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c0f863bb-6e98-404e-928f-f022e10846c9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "With the profiles and the coordinate system in place, we're ready to generate our model:"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "cluster_model = ClusterModel.from_dens_and_tden(\n",
    "    \"cluster_model.hdf5\",\n",
    "    1e-1,\n",
    "    1e4,\n",
    "    gas_profile,\n",
    "    halo_profile,\n",
    "    1000,\n",
    "    coordinate_system=coordinate_system,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2e22ae12-9cd7-4454-bc92-579be4496c34",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The output above tells us exactly what steps were taken to solve to problem:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. The profiles $\\rho_g$ and $\\rho_{\\rm dyn}$ were added to the cluster as fields.\n",
    "2. We then used \"mass accounting\" to construct $\\rho_{\\star}$ (which is zero here because we didn't provide it), and $\\rho_{\\rm dm}$.\n",
    "3. We integrated all of those density profiles to generate the mass profiles.\n",
    "4. We solved the Poisson problem to get $\\Phi$ and $\\nabla \\Phi$.\n",
    "5. We solved the HSE equation\n",
    "\n",
    "   $$ \\frac{\\nabla P}{\\rho_g} = - \\nabla \\Phi. $$\n",
    "\n",
    "6. We used $P$ and $\\rho_g$ to compute the temperature.\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we can take a look at the results! First off, let's take a look at a slice through the cluster of the temperature."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "d1a10481-6904-4c15-8e64-eab2b5864283",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Set the extent of the image (in kpc)\n",
    "extent = [-2000, 2000, -2000, 2000]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create the plot.\n",
    "cluster_model.plot_slice(\"temperature\", extent, cmap=\"inferno\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# show the plot.\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "18cc9f09-fbed-4642-be9e-7fe77fa43670",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can also easily create a 1-D plot of the temperature profile and total mass as a function of the radius:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "id": "54ec64ea-6e34-4589-9447-7deb8bf56336",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Text(0.5, 0, 'Radius, [kpc]')"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 26,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 800x400 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Fetch the radii of the model from its grid manager.\n",
    "radii = cluster_model.get_radii()  # 1-D array of radii.\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fetch the temperature field data.\n",
    "temperature_data = cluster_model.FIELDS[\"temperature\"][...]\n",
    "mass_data = cluster_model.FIELDS[\"total_mass\"][...]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a plot of the two datasets.\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(8, 4), gridspec_kw=dict(wspace=0.4))\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].semilogx(radii, temperature_data, color=\"darkblue\")\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel(\"Temperature, [keV]\")\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel(\"Radius, [kpc]\")\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].loglog(radii, mass_data, color=\"darkblue\")\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel(r\"Total Mass, $[M_{\\odot}]$\")\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel(\"Radius, [kpc]\")"
   ]
  }
